      <!-- 4 Core Requirements -->
      <section id="core-requirements" class="content-section">
        <h2>The 4 Core Requirements for K-1 Petitioners</h2>
        <p>Every I-129F petition is evaluated against these four statutory requirements under INA § 101(a)(15)(K). If any one of them is not met, USCIS will deny the petition — no exceptions.</p>

        <div class="req-cards">
          <div class="req-card req-card-citizenship">
            <div class="req-card-icon">🇺🇸</div>
            <div class="req-card-num">Requirement 1</div>
            <h3>Must Be a U.S. Citizen</h3>
            <p>Only U.S. citizens — whether born or naturalized — can petition for a K-1 visa. Lawful Permanent Residents (green card holders) are explicitly barred from filing a K-1 petition, regardless of how long they have held their green card. If you are an LPR, you must use the CR-1 or F-2A process instead.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="req-card req-card-met">
            <div class="req-card-icon">🤝</div>
            <div class="req-card-num">Requirement 2</div>
            <h3>In-Person Meeting Within 2 Years</h3>
            <p>You and your fiancé(e) must have physically met in person within the two years before filing the I-129F. Video calls, phone calls, or online communication do not count. Waivers exist for extreme hardship or documented religious/cultural customs that prohibit pre-marital meetings.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="req-card req-card-free">
            <div class="req-card-icon">⚖️</div>
            <div class="req-card-num">Requirement 3</div>
            <h3>Both Legally Free to Marry</h3>
            <p>Both you and your fiancé(e) must be legally free to marry under U.S. law. If either party has been married before, all prior marriages must be legally terminated. Provide divorce decrees for each ended marriage, or a death certificate if a prior spouse is deceased. Current marriages — even in separation — are an automatic bar.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="req-card req-card-intent">
            <div class="req-card-icon">💍</div>
            <div class="req-card-num">Requirement 4</div>
            <h3>Bona Fide Intent to Marry Within 90 Days</h3>
            <p>Both parties must have a genuine, mutual intent to marry within 90 days of the beneficiary's admission to the U.S. on the K-1 visa. This is not a soft requirement — if the marriage does not occur within 90 days, the beneficiary must depart. USCIS also reviews whether the intent is genuine (not fraudulent).</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="alert-box alert-info" style="margin-top: 1.5rem;">
          <div class="alert-icon">💡</div>
          <div>
            <strong>On the In-Person Meeting — What Does "Met" Mean?</strong>
            <p>USCIS interprets "met" to mean physical presence in the same location, with awareness of each other's presence. A brief encounter at a group event counts; simply passing through the same city does not. The meeting must be real and verifiable — consular officers will ask for photos, chat logs, flight records, and hotel receipts documenting your trips.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="alert-box alert-warning" style="margin-top: 1rem;">
          <div class="alert-icon">⚠️</div>
          <div>
            <strong>Cultural/Religious Hardship Waiver for the In-Person Requirement</strong>
            <p>If meeting in person would violate strict and long-established customs of your fiancé(e)'s religion or culture, or if meeting would cause extreme hardship to the petitioner, you may request a waiver. Waivers are rare and require substantial documentation. Contact an immigration attorney before assuming you qualify.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- LPR Callout -->
      <div class="lpr-callout">
        <div class="lpr-callout-icon">🚫</div>
        <div>
          <h3>Green Card Holders Cannot Sponsor a K-1 Visa</h3>
          <p>This is the most common misconception about the K-1 visa. If you are a lawful permanent resident — even if you have had your green card for 20 years — you cannot file a K-1 petition. The law explicitly restricts this visa to U.S. citizens only.</p>
          <p>As an LPR, your options are the <SmartLink href="/cr1-visa">CR-1 spousal visa</SmartLink> (you must be married first) or the F-2A immigrant visa category. Both take longer than the K-1 path for citizens. If your priority is speed, naturalizing first — then filing K-1 — may be worth considering.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Financial Requirements -->
      <section id="financial-requirements" class="content-section">
        <h2>Financial Requirements — the I-134 Affidavit of Support</h2>
        <p>At the K-1 visa stage, the petitioner must demonstrate financial ability to support the beneficiary. This is done through <strong>Form I-134, Declaration of Financial Support</strong> — a different (and less strict) form than the I-864 used for spousal visas.</p>

        <div class="alert-box alert-info">
          <div class="alert-icon">📋</div>
          <div>
            <strong>I-134 vs. I-864 — Key Difference</strong>
            <p>The I-134 for K-1 requires you to meet only <strong>100% of the federal poverty guideline</strong> — not the 125% required by the I-864 for CR-1/AOS. The I-134 is also not an enforceable contract (unlike the I-864). However, consular officers have broad discretion, and borderline finances will draw scrutiny. Once you adjust status after marriage, you will file an I-864 at the 125% threshold.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h3>2026 Federal Poverty Guideline — 100% (I-134 K-1 Threshold)</h3>
        <p>Your household size includes you (the petitioner) plus all dependents and the beneficiary. Use the table below to find the minimum income level you should document.</p>

        <div class="income-table-wrap">
          <table class="income-table">
            <thead>
              <tr>
                <th>Household Size</th>
                <th class="col-highlight">100% Poverty Guideline<br/><span class="th-sub">I-134 K-1 minimum</span></th>
                <th>125% Guideline<br/><span class="th-sub">I-864 AOS (later)</span></th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr>
                <td><strong>2 people</strong> <span class="hh-note">(you + fiancé)</span></td>
                <td class="col-highlight"><strong>$20,440</strong></td>
