              </tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <h3>What Income Counts for the I-134?</h3>

        <div class="income-sources-grid">
          <div class="income-col income-yes">
            <h3>Countable Income</h3>
            <ul>
              <li>Wages and salary (W-2 employment)</li>
              <li>Self-employment income (net profit)</li>
              <li>Social Security / SSDI benefits</li>
              <li>Pension and retirement distributions</li>
              <li>Rental income (net after expenses)</li>
              <li>Dividend and investment income</li>
              <li>Military allowances (BAH, BAS)</li>
              <li>Liquid assets (bank, stocks, retirement)</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="income-col income-no">
            <h3>Not Reliably Countable</h3>
            <ul>
              <li>Public benefits (SNAP, Medicaid, SSI)</li>
              <li>Unemployment benefits</li>
              <li>Income not reflected on tax returns</li>
              <li>Anticipated future income (not yet started)</li>
              <li>Personal property value (cars, jewelry)</li>
              <li>Another household member's income (unless joint sponsor)</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h3 style="margin-top: 1.5rem;">What if My Income Is Too Low?</h3>
        <p>If you do not meet the 100% poverty guideline, you have options:</p>
        <ul style="list-style: none; display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 10px; margin: 0.75rem 0 1rem;">
          <li style="display: flex; gap: 10px; align-items: flex-start; font-size: 0.9rem; color: var(--color-muted); line-height: 1.6;">
            <span style="color: #1e40af; font-weight: 700; flex-shrink: 0;">Joint Sponsor</span>
            <span>A separate U.S. citizen or LPR who independently meets the income requirement can submit their own I-134 to supplement yours. They take on financial responsibility alongside you.</span>
          </li>
          <li style="display: flex; gap: 10px; align-items: flex-start; font-size: 0.9rem; color: var(--color-muted); line-height: 1.6;">
            <span style="color: #1e40af; font-weight: 700; flex-shrink: 0;">Assets</span>
            <span>Liquid assets — savings accounts, stocks, retirement funds — can supplement insufficient income. Document them with 12 months of statements. Consular officers apply discretion on how much weight to give assets at the K-1 stage.</span>
          </li>
          <li style="display: flex; gap: 10px; align-items: flex-start; font-size: 0.9rem; color: var(--color-muted); line-height: 1.6;">
            <span style="color: #1e40af; font-weight: 700; flex-shrink: 0;">Job Offer Letter</span>
            <span>If you recently started a new higher-paying job, include your offer letter and first pay stubs even if your last tax return doesn't reflect your current income.</span>
          </li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Documents to Submit with Your I-134</h3>
        <div class="doc-checklist">
          <div class="doc-cat">
            <div class="doc-cat-header">
              <div class="doc-cat-icon">📋</div>
