      <!-- Criminal Background -->
      <section id="criminal-bars" class="content-section">
        <h2>Criminal Background — Bars to Sponsoring</h2>
        <p>Certain criminal convictions permanently or temporarily bar a U.S. citizen from sponsoring a K-1 visa. These are not discretionary — they are statutory bars that USCIS must enforce.</p>

        <div class="bar-cards">
          <div class="bar-card">
            <h3>Adam Walsh Act — Permanent Bar for Crimes Against Minors</h3>
            <p>The Adam Walsh Child Protection and Safety Act permanently bars any U.S. citizen convicted of a "specified offense against a minor" from sponsoring a K-1 petition. Specified offenses include: sexual abuse of a minor, sexual exploitation of minors (including production/possession of child pornography), kidnapping of a minor, and other crimes against children.</p>
            <p>This bar is <strong>absolute</strong>. There is no waiver. It applies even if the conviction was expunged, the sentence was suspended, the person completed probation, or the offense occurred decades ago. USCIS conducts background checks on all petitioners and will discover these convictions.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="bar-card">
            <h3>IMBRA — International Marriage Broker Regulation Act</h3>
            <p>If you met your fiancé(e) through an international marriage broker or matchmaking service, IMBRA requires additional disclosures. You must disclose: all previous K-1 petitions you have filed, all prior marriages, and any criminal convictions including domestic violence, sexual assault, or stalking.</p>
            <p>IMBRA also limits multiple K-1 petitions. If you have had two or more K-1 visas approved through an international marriage broker, USCIS may deny a third without a waiver, even if the prior relationships were legitimate. You must also consent to sharing this information with your fiancé(e).</p>
          </div>
          <div class="bar-card" style="border-color: #d97706; background: #fffbeb;">
            <h3 style="color: #92400e;">Prior Domestic Violence or Crimes Against Persons</h3>
            <p>While not an automatic permanent bar like the Adam Walsh Act, USCIS discretionarily denies K-1 petitions from sponsors with convictions for domestic violence, stalking, harassment, or similar offenses against persons. Officers weigh the nature of the offense, time elapsed, rehabilitation, and risk to the beneficiary. Disclosure is required, and non-disclosure is considered fraud.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="alert-box alert-danger" style="margin-top: 1.25rem;">
          <div class="alert-icon">🚨</div>
          <div>
            <strong>Do Not Omit Criminal History on the I-129F</strong>
            <p>The I-129F asks about all criminal convictions, including arrests, expunged convictions, deferred adjudications, and convictions in foreign countries. Lying or omitting information on a federal immigration form is a federal crime (18 U.S.C. § 1001) and will result in a permanent bar. If you have any criminal history, consult an immigration attorney before filing.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- The I-129F -->
      <section id="i-129f" class="content-section">
        <h2>The I-129F Petition — What the Petitioner Files</h2>
        <p>The <SmartLink href="/i-129f">I-129F, Petition for Alien Fiancé(e)</SmartLink>, is the form the U.S. citizen petitioner files with USCIS to initiate the K-1 visa process. This is the petitioner's primary filing responsibility.</p>

        <div class="alert-box alert-info">
          <div class="alert-icon">📌</div>
          <div>
            <strong>I-129F at a Glance (2026)</strong>
            <p>Filing fee: <strong>$675</strong> | Filed by: U.S. citizen petitioner | Processing time: 10–16 months | Where: USCIS lockbox (address depends on state) | After approval: USCIS → NVC → U.S. Embassy → beneficiary's interview</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h3>What the Petitioner Submits with the I-129F</h3>
        <div class="process-steps">
          <div class="process-step">
            <div class="step-num">1</div>
            <div>
              <strong>Completed Form I-129F</strong>
              <p>Available free at USCIS.gov. Must be signed and dated. File the most current edition — filing an outdated version will result in rejection.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="process-step">
            <div class="step-num">2</div>
            <div>
              <strong>$675 filing fee (check or money order)</strong>
              <p>Payable to "U.S. Department of Homeland Security." Personal checks are accepted. No fee waivers are available for I-129F.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="process-step">
            <div class="step-num">3</div>
            <div>
              <strong>Proof of U.S. citizenship</strong>
              <p>Copy of your U.S. passport (biographical page), U.S. birth certificate, naturalization certificate (N-560/N-565), or Certificate of Citizenship (N-560/N-561).</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="process-step">
            <div class="step-num">4</div>
            <div>
              <strong>Proof of legal status to marry (if previously married)</strong>
              <p>Divorce decree(s) or death certificate(s) for all prior marriages — yours and your fiancé(e)'s. Must be official certified copies. Foreign documents need certified English translations.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="process-step">
            <div class="step-num">5</div>
            <div>
              <strong>Evidence of in-person meeting within the last 2 years</strong>
              <p>Photos together (dated), flight itineraries and boarding passes, hotel records, travel passport stamps, or dated photographs from your meeting(s). The more, the better.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="process-step">
            <div class="step-num">6</div>
            <div>
              <strong>Evidence of bona fide relationship</strong>
              <p>Communication logs (messaging apps, emails), call records, video chat screenshots, evidence of ongoing contact, and any prior visits beyond the initial meeting.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="process-step">
            <div class="step-num">7</div>
            <div>
              <strong>Two passport-style photos of each party (recommended)</strong>
              <p>Some USCIS offices request photos; including them avoids an RFE. Must meet U.S. passport photo specifications.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h3 style="margin-top: 1.5rem;">After I-129F Approval: What Happens Next</h3>
        <p>After USCIS approves the I-129F (typically 10–16 months), the petition is forwarded to the National Visa Center (NVC), which routes it to the U.S. Embassy or Consulate in your fiancé(e)'s country. Your fiancé(e) then completes the consular process — medical exam, DS-160 application, and the K-1 interview. If approved, they receive the K-1 visa and have up to 6 months to use it to enter the U.S. Once in the U.S., you must marry within 90 days.</p>

        <div class="alert-box alert-warning">
          <div class="alert-icon">⏱️</div>
          <div>
            <strong>Processing Time: 10–16 Months</strong>
            <p>As of 2026, I-129F processing at USCIS takes approximately 10 to 16 months, not counting the embassy stage. Check the <SmartLink href="/k1-visa-processing-time">K-1 processing time guide</SmartLink> for current data and how to monitor your case.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Prior Marriages / Multiple K-1 Petitions -->
      <section id="prior-petitions" class="content-section">
        <h2>Prior Marriages and Multiple K-1 Petitions</h2>
        <p>USCIS tracks every K-1 petition you have ever filed and scrutinizes petitioners who have filed multiple times. This is not a disqualifier in itself, but it significantly raises the bar for evidence of a genuine relationship.</p>

        <div class="prior-grid">
          <div class="prior-item prior-ok">
            <span class="prior-num">1</span>
            <span class="prior-label">First K-1 petition — standard scrutiny, normal processing</span>
          </div>
          <div class="prior-item prior-warn">
            <span class="prior-num">2</span>
            <span class="prior-label">Second K-1 petition — heightened scrutiny, expect detailed relationship evidence requests</span>
          </div>
          <div class="prior-item prior-bad">
            <span class="prior-num">3+</span>
            <span class="prior-label">Third+ petition — very high scrutiny; IMBRA waiver may be required if met via marriage broker</span>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="alert-box alert-warning" style="margin-top: 1.25rem;">
          <div class="alert-icon">📝</div>
          <div>
            <strong>Divorce Decrees Are Mandatory for Every Prior Marriage</strong>
            <p>The I-129F requires you to disclose all prior marriages and submit proof that each one ended legally. This applies to both you and your fiancé(e). Missing divorce decrees are one of the most common reasons for Requests for Evidence (RFEs) on I-129F petitions. Gather certified copies of all decrees before filing — foreign documents need certified English translations.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Age Requirements -->
      <section id="age-requirements" class="content-section">
        <h2>Age Requirements</h2>
        <p>Both the petitioner and the beneficiary must be at least 18 years old at the time of filing the I-129F petition, or they must satisfy any applicable state marriage age requirement in the state where they intend to marry. There is no upper age limit for either party.</p>

        <div class="alert-box alert-info">
          <div class="alert-icon">📋</div>
          <div>
            <strong>State Law Controls Minimum Marriage Age</strong>
            <p>U.S. state laws vary on minimum marriage age, and some states have eliminated provisions for underage marriage entirely. USCIS requires that the marriage be legal under the laws of the state where it will occur. Research your state's requirements before the beneficiary enters the U.S.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Can LPR sponsor K-1 -->
      <section id="lpr-cannot-sponsor" class="content-section">
        <h2>Can a Green Card Holder Sponsor a K-1 Visa? No.</h2>
        <p>This is the single most common question we receive about K-1 eligibility, and the answer is unambiguous: <strong>no lawful permanent resident can file a K-1 petition, under any circumstances.</strong></p>

        <div class="split-table-wrap" style="margin-top: 1.25rem;">
          <table class="split-table">
            <thead>
              <tr>
                <th>Petitioner Status</th>
                <th>K-1 Eligible?</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr>
                <td><strong>U.S. citizen (born in U.S.)</strong></td>
                <td>Yes — can file I-129F</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td><strong>U.S. citizen (naturalized)</strong></td>
                <td>Yes — can file I-129F</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td><strong>U.S. citizen by acquisition (born abroad to citizen parent)</strong></td>
                <td>Yes — can file I-129F</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td><strong>Lawful Permanent Resident (LPR / green card holder)</strong></td>
                <td>No — must use CR-1 / F-2A instead</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td><strong>LPR with 30+ years of residency</strong></td>
                <td>No — length of LPR status does not matter</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td><strong>Visa holder (H-1B, F-1, L-1, etc.)</strong></td>
                <td>No — must be a citizen</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td><strong>Undocumented person</strong></td>
                <td>No — cannot file any immigrant petition</td>
              </tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <p style="margin-top: 1.25rem;">If you are an LPR and want to bring your foreign partner to the U.S., your primary options are the <SmartLink href="/cr1-visa">CR-1 spousal visa</SmartLink> (marry first, then file) or the F-2A preference category. Both paths are typically slower than the K-1 path for U.S. citizens. If your partner can wait, you may consider naturalizing — which makes you eligible to file K-1 and may actually produce a faster overall timeline depending on your circumstances.</p>
      </section>

      <!-- Petitioner vs Beneficiary -->
      <section id="who-does-what" class="content-section">
        <h2>Petitioner vs. Beneficiary — Who Does What</h2>
        <p>The K-1 process splits responsibilities clearly between the U.S. petitioner and the foreign beneficiary. Understanding who handles what prevents confusion and missed deadlines.</p>

        <div class="split-table-wrap">
          <table class="split-table">
            <thead>
              <tr>
                <th>U.S. Petitioner's Responsibilities</th>
                <th>Foreign Beneficiary's Responsibilities</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr>
                <td>File Form I-129F with USCIS and pay $675 fee</td>
                <td>Complete DS-160 nonimmigrant visa application online</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>Gather and submit all petitioner-side evidence</td>
                <td>Schedule and attend K-1 visa interview at U.S. Embassy</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>Submit Form I-134 (financial support declaration)</td>
                <td>Attend K-1 medical examination by approved physician</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>Provide proof of U.S. citizenship</td>
                <td>Gather and bring all beneficiary documents to interview</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>Provide proof of in-person meeting</td>
                <td>Obtain police clearances from every country of residence</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>Provide divorce decrees for all prior marriages (petitioner's)</td>
                <td>Provide divorce decrees for all prior marriages (beneficiary's)</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>Track USCIS case status (IOE/EAC receipt number)</td>
                <td>Pay visa issuance fee at embassy (if applicable)</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>Marry the beneficiary within 90 days of U.S. entry</td>
                <td>Enter U.S. on K-1 visa and adjust status after marriage</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>File I-485 (Adjustment of Status) jointly after marriage</td>
                <td>Attend AOS interview and biometrics</td>
              </tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Common Disqualifiers -->
      <section id="disqualifiers" class="content-section">
        <h2>Common Disqualifiers — 8 Reasons a K-1 Petition Gets Denied</h2>
        <p>Being aware of these red flags before you file can save you months of delay or a permanent bar.</p>

        <div class="disq-list">
          <div class="disq-item">
            <div class="disq-icon">1</div>
            <div>
              <strong>Petitioner is not a U.S. citizen</strong>
              <p>Green card holders, visa holders, and undocumented persons cannot file. There is no workaround for this requirement.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="disq-item">
            <div class="disq-icon">2</div>
            <div>
              <strong>Never met in person (or meeting was more than 2 years ago)</strong>
              <p>Online-only relationships do not qualify. If more than 2 years have passed since your last in-person meeting, you may need to plan another visit before filing, or apply for a waiver.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="disq-item">
            <div class="disq-icon">3</div>
            <div>
              <strong>Either party is still legally married</strong>
              <p>A pending divorce, separated (but not divorced) spouse, or any undissolved marriage from any country makes both parties ineligible until the prior marriage is legally terminated.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="disq-item">
            <div class="disq-icon">4</div>
            <div>
              <strong>Adam Walsh Act conviction on record</strong>
              <p>Any conviction for a specified offense against a minor is a permanent, non-waivable bar to K-1 sponsorship. USCIS background checks will surface this.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="disq-item">
            <div class="disq-icon">5</div>
            <div>
              <strong>Income below the poverty threshold with no joint sponsor or assets</strong>
              <p>If the consular officer determines you cannot financially support the beneficiary and you have no joint sponsor or documented assets, the visa may be denied under INA § 212(a)(4) as a public charge.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="disq-item">
            <div class="disq-icon">6</div>
            <div>
              <strong>Missing divorce decrees for prior marriages</strong>
              <p>One of the top RFE triggers. Every prior marriage for both parties must be documented with a certified divorce decree or death certificate. Foreign documents must be translated.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="disq-item">
            <div class="disq-icon">7</div>
            <div>
              <strong>Insufficient evidence of a genuine relationship</strong>
              <p>USCIS officers adjudicating the I-129F look for evidence of ongoing, authentic contact. Sparse communication records, inability to describe the fiancé's background, or evidence suggesting the relationship is primarily for immigration benefit will result in denial.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="disq-item">
            <div class="disq-icon">8</div>
            <div>
              <strong>Misrepresentation or fraud on the petition</strong>
              <p>Any false statement — even a minor omission — on the I-129F or at any point in the K-1 process can result in permanent inadmissibility for the beneficiary and federal charges for the petitioner. When in doubt, disclose and consult an attorney.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- FAQ -->
      <section id="faq" class="content-section">
        <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
        <div class="faq-list">
          <details class="faq-item">
            <summary>Can a green card holder sponsor a K-1 visa?</summary>
            <p>No. Only U.S. citizens can petition for a K-1 fiancé visa. Lawful permanent residents (green card holders) cannot file a K-1 petition regardless of how long they have held their green card. LPRs who want to bring a foreign spouse to the U.S. must use the CR-1 spousal visa or F-2A immigrant visa category. If speed is a priority, an LPR may consider naturalizing first — then filing K-1 as a citizen — as this can sometimes produce a faster overall outcome.</p>
          </details>
          <details class="faq-item">
            <summary>What if I don't meet the income requirement for the K-1 visa?</summary>
            <p>If your income falls below 100% of the federal poverty guideline for your household size, you have several options: (1) Use a joint sponsor — a U.S. citizen or LPR who independently meets the income requirement and files a separate I-134 on your behalf; (2) Supplement with assets — liquid assets such as bank savings, stocks, or retirement funds can offset insufficient income; (3) Include a recent pay raise not yet on your taxes — use recent pay stubs and an employer letter to document your current income. The consular officer makes the final determination on financial ability at the K-1 interview stage.</p>
          </details>
          <details class="faq-item">
            <summary>What is the 2-year in-person meeting rule for the K-1 visa?</summary>
            <p>U.S. law requires that the petitioner and beneficiary have physically met each other in person within the two years immediately preceding the filing of the I-129F petition. A video call, phone call, or online meeting does not satisfy this requirement — physical presence in the same location is mandatory. Waivers are available only on the grounds of extreme hardship to the petitioner or if meeting in person would violate strict and long-established customs of the beneficiary's culture or religion. Waivers are rarely granted and require substantial documentation.</p>
          </details>
          <details class="faq-item">
            <summary>How many K-1 petitions can I file in my lifetime?</summary>
            <p>There is no absolute numerical cap, but USCIS tracks all prior K-1 petitions you have filed. If you have had two or more prior K-1 petitions approved, USCIS will scrutinize your new petition heavily and may request extensive evidence that your current relationship is genuine. Additionally, under IMBRA, if you met your fiancé(e) through an international marriage broker, you are limited to two K-1 approvals in your lifetime without a waiver. A history of multiple K-1 petitions — particularly to beneficiaries from the same country — is a red flag that USCIS takes seriously.</p>
          </details>
          <details class="faq-item">
            <summary>What is the Adam Walsh Act and how does it affect K-1 sponsorship?</summary>
            <p>The Adam Walsh Child Protection and Safety Act permanently bars anyone convicted of a "specified offense against a minor" from petitioning for a K-1 visa. Specified offenses include sexual abuse, sexual exploitation of minors, kidnapping of a minor, and other crimes against children. This bar is absolute — there is no waiver available in the K-1 context. It applies even if the conviction was expunged, the sentence was suspended, or significant time has passed. USCIS conducts background checks on all petitioners and will discover these convictions through FBI records.</p>
          </details>
          <details class="faq-item">
            <summary>Do I need a lawyer to file the I-129F?</summary>
            <p>You are not legally required to hire an attorney to file Form I-129F. Many couples successfully self-file the K-1 petition with straightforward circumstances. However, an immigration attorney is strongly recommended if: you have any criminal history, you have filed prior K-1 petitions, your income is borderline, there are prior immigration violations by either party, or your situation involves a cultural/religious hardship waiver for the in-person meeting requirement. Attorney fees typically range from $1,500 to $3,500 for I-129F representation. The USCIS filing fee is $675 regardless of whether you use an attorney.</p>
          </details>
        </div>
      </section>

